"CORE_NARRATIVE: Current light field depth estimation relies on the EPI linearity assumption, which is fundamentally broken by ubiquitous Non-Lambertian surfaces, causing severe depth artifacts in real-world deployments. To bridge this gap, we introduce a three-layer angular signal decomposition physical model and a Geometric Dual-Mask network to decouple material reflections from geometric depth. This physically grounded routing mechanism fundamentally resolves depth estimation failures caused by Non-Lambertian interference, enabling robust deployment in complex physical scenarios.\n\nINTRO_HOOK: Open with a compelling real-world scenario, such as autonomous driving past reflective vehicles, where ubiquitous Non-Lambertian surfaces cause catastrophic depth estimation failures. This immediately highlights the critical flaw of the EPI linearity assumption and sets the stage for addressing Non-Lambertian interference in complex physical deployments.\n\nGAP_BRIDGE: Conclude the related work by emphasizing that existing data-driven or heuristic approaches merely mask out specular highlights rather than physically decoupling material reflections from geometric depth. This limitation necessitates our transition to a physics-driven approach, where the three-layer angular signal decomposition explicitly isolates Non-Lambertian residuals to preserve underlying depth cues.\n\nMETHOD_JUSTIFY: The three-layer angular signal decomposition is explicitly designed to decouple the light field into ambient, depth, and material residual components, directly addressing the physical root cause of EPI linearity breakdown. Consequently, the Geometric Dual-Mask network utilizes these decoupled geometric angular features to adaptively route features, ensuring that Non-Lambertian interference is neutralized without discarding valuable spatial context.\n\nEXPERIMENT_VALIDATE: Design experiments to specifically evaluate performance on multi-domain datasets rich in Non-Lambertian materials (e.g., UrbanLF-Syn), proving that our domain-balanced framework maintains robustness across diverse physical scenarios. Furthermore, use ablation studies to demonstrate that the geometric angular feature classification (achieving 0.962 AUC) and dual-mask routing are the direct causes of the eliminated depth artifacts.\n\nCONCLUSION_ECHO: Reiterate that by decoupling angular signals via physical priors and dual-mask routing, we have fundamentally resolved the depth estimation failures historically caused by Non-Lambertian surface reflections. Conclude by emphasizing that this breakthrough transforms light field depth estimation from a fragile, assumption-bound tool into a robust solution ready for practical deployment in autonomous driving and robotics."